const faqs = [
 { q: 'What do HVAC workers wear?', a: 'HVAC service techs in residential roles typically wear embroidered polos with the company logo, technician name, and Nevada State Contractors Board license number. Commercial and install crews wear mechanic-style work shirts (Red Kap SP14 or SY24) with woven name patches. In summer, both groups switch to moisture-wicking poly fabrics to handle 110°+ ambient and 130°+ attic temperatures.' },
 { q: 'What\'s the best uniform for HVAC techs in Vegas summer?', a: 'Moisture-wicking polo (Port Authority K540) for residential service or moisture-wicking work shirt (Red Kap SY24) for commercial. Cotton-blend shirts soak through by 11 AM in July; performance fabrics keep wicking even after multiple service calls. Pair with vented work pants and a wide-brim cap for outdoor unit work.' },
 { q: 'Do HVAC techs wear FR shirts?', a: 'Most residential and light commercial HVAC techs don\'t need FR. FR is required for techs working on energized electrical panels (some commercial mechanical service) or in environments with arc-flash risk. Most HVAC service work is non-FR; the safety officer determines whether FR is required for specific roles or jobs.' },
 { q: 'What pants do HVAC techs wear?', a: 'Carhartt B11 work pants and Red Kap PT20/PT88 industrial work pants are the most-ordered. Some techs prefer Carhartt B324 carpenter pants with reinforced double-knee panels for crews doing a lot of attic and crawlspace work where the knees take constant abuse.' },
 { q: 'What\'s the dress code for an HVAC service tech?', a: 'Standard residential service: branded company polo with embroidered name and license number, work pants (Carhartt or Red Kap), closed-toe work boots, and a branded cap. The look should communicate "professional service business" the moment a homeowner opens the door — clean, branded, identifiable.' },
 { q: 'How many uniforms does an HVAC service tech need?', a: 'A typical baseline is 5 polos (or work shirts) per tech for a standard work week rotation, plus 2-3 work pants, 1 hoodie or quarter-zip for cool mornings, and 1-2 caps. Service techs working through Vegas summer often add 2-3 extra moisture-wicking polos to handle the rotation when shirts soak through during a day.' },
 { q: 'Where can I get custom HVAC uniforms in Las Vegas?', a: 'Bighorn Threads outfits Vegas HVAC and plumbing service shops with embroidered polos, mechanic-style work shirts, branded outerwear, and hard hat decals. We integrate with industrial laundry programs and pre-decorate shirts to match laundry inventory codes when needed.' },
]

