 <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 py-16 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">

 <aside class="mb-10 border border-hairline bg-panel p-7">
 <p class="mb-3 font-mono text-[10px] font-bold uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-gold-600">Quick Answer</p>
 <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-charcoal sm:text-xl">Las Vegas HVAC service techs wear moisture-wicking embroidered polos (Port Authority K540) for residential service work and Red Kap mechanic-style work shirts (SY24 Performance Plus) for commercial mechanical and install crews. Both feature company logo, technician name, and Nevada State Contractors Board license number. In summer, performance poly fabric is non-negotiable for 110°+ ambient and 130°+ attic temperatures.</p>
 </aside>

 <h2 id="why-it-matters" class="mt-12 mb-4 font-heading text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">Why HVAC Uniforms Are a Sales Tool</h2>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-charcoal">An HVAC service call is a trust transaction. The homeowner is letting a stranger into their house to diagnose, charge, and repair a system they don\'t understand. The visual cues at the front door — clean uniformed tech, embroidered company logo, name on the chest, license number visible — close the trust gap before the tech speaks. A tech in a random t-shirt with a clipboard does the opposite.</p>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-charcoal">For commercial mechanical service, the same logic applies in a different form: facility managers and building owners are looking for evidence the contracting company runs a professional operation. Coordinated branded uniforms across the crew is one of the cheapest, fastest signals a contractor can send.</p>

 <h2 id="role-spec" class="mt-12 mb-4 font-heading text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">Uniforms by Role</h2>

 <h3 class="mt-8 mb-3 font-heading text-xl font-bold">Residential Service Techs</h3>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-charcoal">Front-of-house apparel. Standard kit:</p>
 <ul class="mb-6 list-disc pl-6 space-y-3 text-lg leading-relaxed text-charcoal">
 <li><strong>Embroidered moisture-wicking polo</strong> (Port Authority K540 Silk Touch Performance) with company logo on left chest, employee name on right chest</li>
 <li><strong>Carhartt B11 work pants</strong> or similar — durable, comfortable for crawl spaces and attic work</li>
 <li><strong>Branded service cap</strong> (Richardson 112 trucker hat with embroidered logo)</li>
 <li><strong>Closed-toe work boots</strong> — separate from the workwear program</li>
 </ul>

 <h3 class="mt-8 mb-3 font-heading text-xl font-bold">Commercial / Install Crews</h3>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-charcoal">Heavier-duty apparel for new install and commercial mechanical service. Standard kit:</p>
 <ul class="mb-6 list-disc pl-6 space-y-3 text-lg leading-relaxed text-charcoal">
 <li><strong>Red Kap SY24 Performance Plus Work Shirt</strong> — moisture-wicking poly version of the SP14, dual-button-front, two chest pockets</li>
 <li><strong>Red Kap PT20 or PT88 work pants</strong> — durable, industrial-laundry-compatible</li>
 <li><strong>Branded jacket or quarter-zip</strong> for cool desert mornings</li>
 <li><strong>ANSI 107 hi-vis vest</strong> — required on jobsites with active vehicle traffic, crane operations, or sitewide hi-vis specs</li>
 </ul>

 <h3 class="mt-8 mb-3 font-heading text-xl font-bold">Office Staff and Dispatchers</h3>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-charcoal">Lighter-weight branded polos for the front counter and dispatcher roles where customers walk in or video calls happen. Same Port Authority blank as service techs but in a slightly different colorway, often without the name embroidery.</p>

 <h3 class="mt-8 mb-3 font-heading text-xl font-bold">Service Managers and Supervisors</h3>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-charcoal">Differentiated colorway or polo upgrade — Cutter & Buck DryTec or Travis Mathew performance polo for client meetings and on-site supervision. Visual signal of authority without breaking the brand consistency.</p>

 <h2 id="vegas-summer" class="mt-12 mb-4 font-heading text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">Vegas Summer Specifics</h2>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-charcoal">HVAC techs are the trade most-exposed to extreme heat in Vegas summer. Attic and rooftop work hits 130°+ surface temperatures from June through September, and the AC repair calls themselves come during the hottest hours. Three things matter:</p>
 <ul class="mb-6 list-disc pl-6 space-y-3 text-lg leading-relaxed text-charcoal">
 <li><strong>Moisture-wicking fabric.</strong> Cotton blends soak through and stay wet. Performance polyester (Port Authority K540, Sport-Tek ST650) wicks sweat and dries between calls.</li>
 <li><strong>Light colorways.</strong> Light gray, khaki, or sand colors absorb 30-40% less solar radiation than dark colors. Some HVAC companies switch to lighter summer colorways while maintaining brand consistency through embroidered logos in brand colors.</li>
 <li><strong>Adequate rotation.</strong> 5 polos covers a normal week, but Vegas summer often requires 7+ as techs go through 2 shirts per day during heat-stress conditions. <a href="https://www.osha.gov/heat-exposure" rel="noopener" class="text-gold-600 underline decoration-gold-600/40 underline-offset-4 hover:decoration-gold-600">OSHA heat exposure guidance</a> recommends adequate hydration and shaded breaks; clean dry shirts is a smaller but real component.</li>
 </ul>

 <h2 id="branding-spec" class="mt-12 mb-4 font-heading text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">Branding Spec</h2>
 <ul class="mb-6 list-disc pl-6 space-y-3 text-lg leading-relaxed text-charcoal">
 <li><strong>Left chest:</strong> Company logo, 3-3.5 inches wide, embroidered</li>
 <li><strong>Right chest:</strong> Employee first name embroidered (most service shops use first name only)</li>
 <li><strong>Sleeve or back collar:</strong> Nevada State Contractors Board license number — Nevada customers expect to see it</li>
 <li><strong>Back yoke (optional):</strong> Service phone number for fleet-vehicle visibility when techs are working on outdoor units</li>
 </ul>

 <h2 id="industrial-laundry" class="mt-12 mb-4 font-heading text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">Industrial Laundry Programs</h2>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-charcoal">Most HVAC shops with 10+ techs run industrial laundry programs through Cintas, Vestis, or Prudential Uniforms. The laundry company processes shirts on a weekly rotation, replaces damaged garments, and bills monthly. <a href="/industries/plumbing-hvac-las-vegas/" class="text-gold-600 underline decoration-gold-600/40 underline-offset-4 hover:decoration-gold-600">Plumbing and HVAC service uniforms</a> covers the laundry-program decision in more depth.</p>

